{"id":1030,"date":"2014-01-20T12:05:59","date_gmt":"2014-01-20T20:05:59","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/?p=1030"},"modified":"2016-02-07T07:21:02","modified_gmt":"2016-02-07T15:21:02","slug":"je-reve-jai-fait-un-reve-jai-un-reve-aujourdhui","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/2014\/01\/je-reve-jai-fait-un-reve-jai-un-reve-aujourdhui\/","title":{"rendered":"Je r\u00eave, J&#8217;ai fait un r\u00eave, J&#8217;ai un r\u00eave aujourd&#8217;hui"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1036\" alt=\"Je_reve_header\" src=\"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header-1024x145.png\" width=\"625\" height=\"88\" srcset=\"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header-1024x145.png 1024w, https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header-300x42.png 300w, https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header-624x88.png 624w, https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2014\/01\/Je_reve_header.png 1800w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>Martin Luther King\u2019s famous \u201cI have a dream\u201d speech poses a challenge when translating to other languages (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=1UV1fs8lAbg\" target=\"_blank\">video in original English<\/a>). As with all powerful language, the act of translation causes us to interpret the words. Marie Walburg Plouviez interpreted and recorded this historic speech: <a href=\"https:\/\/www.mightyverse.com\/en\/phrase_lists\/i-have-a-dream-in-french\" target=\"_blank\">&#8220;I have a dream&#8221; in French<\/a>, and in doing so, shared with us some of the implications of a French interpretation.<\/p>\n<p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"On Translating I Have a Dream in French with Marie\" width=\"625\" height=\"352\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/MzQcvyrxLpA?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen><\/iframe><\/p>\n<p>In English, \u201cI have a dream\u201d in the present tense can only refer to a vision for the future (rather than the more common\u00a0<a href=\"http:\/\/www.oxforddictionaries.com\/us\/definition\/american_english\/dream\" target=\"_blank\">meaning of dream<\/a>,\u00a0\u201ca series of thoughts, images, and sensations occurring in a person\u2019s mind during sleep\u201d). This phrase is often translated into french &#8220;J&#8217;ai fait un r\u00eave&#8221; using the verb \u201c<a href=\"http:\/\/french.about.com\/od\/verb_conjugations\/a\/faire.htm\" target=\"_blank\">faire<\/a>,\u201d which translates literally as &#8220;I make a dream&#8221; or \u201cI am doing the dream.\u201d Another approach is to use the present tense with the verb \u201c<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wiktionary.org\/wiki\/r%C3%AAver#French\" target=\"_blank\">r\u00eaver<\/a>\u201d (\u201cto dream\u201d). \u201cJe r\u00eave\u201d literally \u201cI dream.\u201d Marie uses three different translations to reinforce different connotations. The third creates the feeling of immediacy with the translation \u201cJ&#8217;ai un r\u00eave aujourd&#8217;hui\u201d using the verb \u201c<a href=\"http:\/\/french.about.com\/od\/verb_conjugations\/a\/avoir.htm\" target=\"_blank\">avoir<\/a>\u201d (\u201cto have\u201d).<\/p>\n<p>We are enthralled by beautiful language. Even more so when the language is rich in meaning and purpose. Part of what makes this speech powerful is the repetition of the word \u201cdream\u201d in multiple contexts. Martin Luther King starts by evoking \u201cthe American dream.\u201d Then he repeats the phrase \u201cI have a dream\u201d and \u201cI have a dream today.\u201d These two phrases transform the vision from the almost fantasy of Mississippi as \u201can oasis of freedom and justice\u201d to a call to action that we make this vision happen within our lifetime. He conveys urgency with a vision that his four little children \u201cwill one day live in a nation where they will not be judged by the color of their skin but by the content of their character.\u201d<\/p>\n<p>Few speeches have captivated the mind and the heart so completely as Martin Luther King\u2019s I have a Dream speech, from August 28th, 1963. Last year we provided a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.mightyverse.com\/es\/phrase_lists\/martin-luther-king-dream.html\" target=\"_blank\">Spanish translation with English recording<\/a>, and this year we continue the tradition with <a href=\"https:\/\/www.mightyverse.com\/en\/phrase_lists\/i-have-a-dream-in-french\" target=\"_blank\">French recording and translation<\/a>\u00a0of phrases from an excerpt of the speech.<\/p>\n<p>In our interview with Marie, she refers to Le Monde&#8217;s interpretation. \u00a0Along with their 2013 article, you can watch the\u00a0<a href=\"http:\/\/www.lemonde.fr\/culture\/article\/2013\/08\/28\/martin-luther-king_3465114_3246.html\" target=\"_blank\">full video with French subtitles<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>Our mission at Mightyverse is to provide a place where all languages are equal, yet we celebrate their differences and richness of expression. As is so often the case, the translation can take the language into directions not anticipated and through the effort of poetic interpretation can make the language come alive anew.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Martin Luther King\u2019s famous \u201cI have a dream\u201d speech poses a challenge when translating to other languages (video in original English). As with all powerful language, the act of translation causes us to interpret the words. Marie Walburg Plouviez interpreted and recorded this historic speech: &#8220;I have a dream&#8221; in French, and in doing so, [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":83,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[1],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1030"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/83"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=1030"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1030\/revisions"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=1030"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=1030"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/blog.mightyverse.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=1030"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}